:INFO
What Grit Numbers Mean
Grit refers to the coarseness of abrasive particles embedded in the stone. \
A low number means large particles and fast metal removal. A high number \
means fine particles and a polished, refined edge. The right starting grit \
depends entirely on the condition of your knife, not personal preference.

:COUNTER.half
120 to 400 Grit
Repair, chips, and reprofiling
|
:COUNTER.half
1000 Grit
Primary sharpening for dull knives

:COUNTER.half
3000 to 4000 Grit
Refining and edge setting
|
:COUNTER.half
6000 to 8000 Grit
Polishing and finishing

:PATH
Diagnose Your Knife First
Run your fingernail lightly across the edge perpendicular to the blade. A \
sharp edge bites and catches. A dull edge slides off cleanly. A damaged \
edge feels uneven or rough along its length. Chips and missing metal require \
starting at 200 to 400 grit. A knife that simply stopped cutting starts at \
1000 grit. A well-maintained knife used weekly starts at 3000 grit.

:PATH
The Standard Two-Stone Progression
For most home cooks, two stones cover every situation: a 1000-grit stone for \
sharpening and a 6000-grit stone for finishing. Sharpen on the coarser stone \
until a full burr forms from heel to tip on both sides. Move to the finer stone \
to refine and deburr. This combination works on Japanese knives, Western knives, \
and single-bevel knives sharpened on the flat face only.

:CHECKLIST
Choosing Your First Stones
[ ] 1000-grit splash-and-go stone (King KW-65 or Shapton Pro 1000) for sharpening
[ ] 6000-grit finishing stone (King 6000 or Naniwa Chocera 3000) for polishing
[ ] Diamond lapping plate or stone fixer to keep stones flat over time
[ ] Stone holder or wet kitchen towel to prevent movement while working

:NOTE
Flatten Your Stones Regularly
Stones hollow in the center with use. A dished stone produces a convex edge, \
rounding the apex rather than sharpening it. Flatten your stones by rubbing \
them against each other under running water in figure-eight patterns, or use \
a diamond lapping plate. A flat stone is as important as grit selection. \
Check flatness every few sessions with a straight edge.

:INFO
Ceramic Rods and Honing Steels
A honing rod does not sharpen. It realigns an edge that has rolled without \
removing significant metal. Use a smooth ceramic rod at 15 to 20 degrees, \
five passes per side, before every cooking session. This extends weeks between \
full stone sharpenings. A grooved steel is aggressive and suited to very dull \
or thick Western blades only.

:QUOTE
The goal is not a mirror edge. The goal is an edge that stays sharp through a week of cooking.

